'''Alec Yasinsac''' is the Dean of the School of Computing, [[University of South Alabama]], United States.<ref>[http://www.soc.southalabama.edu/index.php/facultyandstaff- Faculty and staff listing] {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20121211182533/http://www.soc.southalabama.edu/index.php/facultyandstaff- |date=2012-12-11 }}, [[University of South Alabama]] SoC, retrieved 2012-06-26.</ref><ref name="autobio">[http://www.soc.southalabama.edu/~yasinsac/biography.html Biography from Yasinsac's web site], retrieved 2012-06-26.</ref>
A retired [[U.S. Marine]],<ref name="vf"/> Yasinsac was awarded his doctoral degree in 1996 from the [[University of Virginia]], where his doctoral advisor was [[William Wulf]].<ref name="autobio"/><ref>[http://people.engr.ncsu.edu/txie/sefamily.htm Software Engineering Academic Genealogy], Tao Xie, NCSU, retrieved 2010-01-27.</ref> He received the Master of Science in Computer Science from the [[Naval Postgraduate School]] and Bachelor of Science in [[Mathematics]] from [[Appalachian State University]].<ref name="autobio"/>
Yasinsac is the co-founder and co-director of the Security and Assurance in Information Security (SAIT) Laboratory. He was a visiting scholar at the [[National Academy of Engineering]] (NAE) in 2006,<ref name="vf">[http://www.nae.edu/File.aspx?id=7402 Visiting Scholar and New Mirzayan Fellows] (2006), ''The Bridge'' (NAE) '''36''' (4): 64.</ref> served on the advisory board for the NAE 2007 National Meeting Symposium on Electronic Voting,<ref name="autobio"/> and led the team that conducted the source code review in support of the Florida Department of State audit of [[Florida's 13th congressional district]] 2006 election.<ref>[http://www.nae.edu/Publications/TheBridge/Archives/V-37-2VotingTechnologies/WhatHappenedinSarasotaCounty.aspx What Happened in Sarasota County?], David Jefferson (2007), ''The Bridge'' (NAE) '''37''' (2).</ref>
